Conceptual Questions¶

Q1. Let’s examine the differences between LDA and QDA.¶

a) If the Bayes decision boundary is linear, do we expect LDA or QDA to perform better on the training set? What about in the test set?¶

If the Bayes decision boundary is linear, do we expect LDA to perform well in test set. while QDA might perform better in training set. This is because QDA has more flexibilty and will fit the training set more accurately.

b) If the Bayes decision boundary is non-linear, do we expect LDA or QDA to perform better on the training set? On the test set?¶

If the Bayes decision boundary is non-linear, we would expect QDA to perform better on both the training and test sets. QDA can model non-linear decision boundaries more accurately than LDA due to its flexibility in allowing different covariance matrices for each class.

c)In general, as the sample size n increases, do we expect the test prediction accuracy of QDA relative to LDA to improve, decline, or be unchanged? Why?¶

As the sample size n increases, we would expect the test prediction accuracy of QDA relative to LDA to improve. As the sample size n increases, the estimates of the covariance matrices in QDA become more reliable. QDA can then better capture the true underlying covariance structure of the data, leading to improved performance and higher test prediction accuracy relative to LDA.

d)True or False:¶

Even if the Bayes decision boundary for a given problem is linear, we will probably achieve a superior test error rate using QDA rather than LDA because QDA is flexible enough to model a linear decision boundary.

False. If the Bayes decision boundary for a given problem is linear, and the assumptions of LDA hold true (such as a common covariance matrix for all classes), then LDA is expected to achieve a superior test error rate compared to QDA.

Q2) In relation to the odds and the Default dataset¶

a) On average, what fraction of people with an odds of 0.37 of defaulting on their credit card payment will in fact default?¶

The probability of an event $E$ with a $O(A)$ occurring is $ \frac{O(A)}{1+O(A)}$ $$ P(A) = = \frac{O(A)}{(1+O(A))} = \frac{0.37}{(1+0.37)} = 0.2700729927 $$ 0.2700729927 of the people will default on their credit card payment given the odds are 0.37

b) Suppose that an individual has a 16% chance of defaulting on their credit card payment. What are the odds that they will default?¶

The odds of an event $E$ with a probability $P(A)$ occurring is $ \frac{P(A)}{1-P(A)}$ $$ Odds(A) = \frac{P(A)}{(1-P(A))} = \frac{0.16}{(1-0.16)} = 0.19047619047 $$ There the odds that they will default is 0.19048

Q3. Suppose that we take a data set, divide it into equally sized training and test sets, and then try out two different classification procedures. First, we use logistic regression and get an error rate of 20% on the training data and 30% on the test data. Next we use 1-nearest neighbors (i.e. K=1) and get an average error rate (averaged over both test and training data sets) of 18%. Based on these results, which method should we prefer to use for classification of new observations? Why?¶

Using K-nearest neighbors (KNN) with K=1 can lead to overfitting and in poor generalization to unseen data. This model may capture noise or outliers present in the training data. This is because for a given point $x_i$ we are looking at DataSet $X$ and see which point is closest. For the training data, it means the prediciton will always will be correct. Hence the training error should be $0\%$. Hence the training error should be $18\% x 2$ which is $ 36\% $. Hence the logistic Regression performs better with 30% error in test data. Therefore we should prefer logistic regression

# BEGIN SOLUTION
def metrics_score(actual, predicted, columns):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))
    print("Confusion Matrix:")
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = columns, yticklabels = columns)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    return cm
# END SOLUTION

for feature in df.columns:
    if feature in ["name", "mpg01", "mpg"]:
        continue
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(21, 6))
    # plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.boxplot(x='mpg01', y=feature, data=df, ax=axs[0])
    axs[0].set_title(f'Boxplot of {feature} vs. mpg01')
    # plt.show()

    # plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.violinplot(x='mpg01', y=feature, data=df, ax=axs[1])
    axs[1].set_title(f'Violinplot of {feature} vs. mpg01')
    # plt.show()

    # plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(y=feature, x='mpg01', data=df, ax=axs[2])
    axs[2].set_title(f'Scatterplot of {feature} vs. mpg01')
    fig.suptitle(f"{feature} vs. mpg01")
    plt.show()

Conclusions:

  • Cars with mpg above the median (mpg01=1) are predominantly 4-cylinder vehicles. This is supported by both the boxplot and violin plot, showing a clear association between the number of cylinders and mpg01. In contrast, cars with mpg below the median (mpg01=0) are more evenly distributed across 6 and 8 cylinders.

  • Cars with mpg below the median (mpg01=0) tend to have higher values for displacement, horsepower, and weight compared to cars with mpg above the median (mpg01=1). Among these variables, only displacement shows a wider spread of data for cars with mpg below the median.

  • There is a positive trend between the year of the car and its mpg, indicating that newer cars tend to have higher mpg values. This is evident in the boxplot and violinplot of year vs. mpg01, where the points for cars with mpg above the median (mpg01=1) are generally clustered towards top, indicating higher year values.

  • Cars with mpg below the median (mpg01=0) are more likely to be of American origin (origin=1), while cars with higher mpg values tend to be of European (origin=2) or Japanese (origin=3) origin. This is supported by the countplot of origin vs. mpg01.

  • Acceleration appears to be higher for cars with higher mpg values and lower for cars with lower mpg values. This is evident in the plots of acceleration vs. mpg01, where the points for cars with mpg above the median (mpg01=1) are generally clustered towards the top, indicating higher acceleration values.

Overall, these findings suggest that the number of cylinders, displacement, horsepower, weight, year, origin, and acceleration are all important factors in predicting whether a car has high or low gas mileage.

classes = [f"mpg <= {median_mpg}(median)", f"mpg > {median_mpg}(median)"]
X = df.drop(['mpg', 'mpg01', 'name'], axis=1)
Y = df['mpg01']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3, random_state=4)
sc = StandardScaler()
x_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
x_train = pd.DataFrame(x_train, columns = X_train.columns)
x_test = sc.transform(X_test)
x_test = pd.DataFrame(x_test, columns=X_test.columns)

Logistic Regression has the highest accuracy and F1-scores for both classes, indicating a slightly better overall performance compared to LDA and QDA.

Conclusion

  • All three models perform relatively well, with accuracies ranging from 91% to 93%.
  • LDA assumes equal covariance matrices for each class, while QDA allows for different covariance matrices. In this case, LDA performs slightly better, possibly because the assumption of equal covariance matrices holds true or because the data is better suited to a linear decision boundary.
  • Logistic Regression outperforms LDA, which suggests that the data might have very slight deviation from the assumption of equal covariance matrices
  • The performance is quite similar, with Logistic Regression having a slight edge in accuracy and F1-scores. This suggests that the linear decision boundary of Logistic Regression is sufficient for this dataset, and the assumption of different covariance matrices in QDA might not be necessary. Also note that we have equal classes as we have split by median.
